Whether you’re a seasoned lifter or just starting your strength journey, this is your opportunity to represent FEU, build your strength, and carry the Tamaraw pride on and off the platform. 🐃💪

If powerlifting speaks to your strength, we humbly ask you to take a moment to answer our form. Your response can help shape the future of FEU’s lifting community.

Let’s lift FEU together!

Overnight, Morayta and España Boulevard were submerged in knee-deep waters following the recent monsoon rains in Metro Manila and other cities in Luzon, and students scrambled to keep their books and uniforms dry. For ordinary Filipinos, floods mean disruption and loss, but for the privileged, they are no more than scenery outside their condo windows. Such is the advantage of being a ‘nepo baby’—a child of privilege that inherits not just wealth, but the luxury of staying dry through storms.

# I think I’ll never use the ENB elevators again
## ‼️ posting this for awareness and TO ask for help ‼️ 

I want to get this off my chest kasi until now, traumatized pa rin ako sa ginawa sakin ng isang student, kung sino ka man.

Around 10:56 AM yesterday, kaka-dismiss lang namin and nasa 7th floor pa kami ng engineering building. Our next class was at 11:00 AM sa 6th floor ng Tech. Siyempre, nagmamadali kami kasi kailangan pa mag-prepare at lilipat ng building. Alam namin kung gaano katagal pumila sa elevators kasi yung iba sira pa. Luckily, may elevator na nagbukas. We thought kasya kami so sumakay kami. May ilang humabol din na students, and since may space pa, sumakay sila.

Pero pagka-close ng door, out of nowhere, bigla akong tinulak. Not just lightly eh, yung tulak na padabog, agresibo, na para bang wala kang respeto. I froze for a second kasi nagulat ako sa ganung behavior. I tried to move a little kasi baka sobrang nasisikipan na siya. Hindi naman kami naglalaro or naghaharutan ng friends ko. Ni hindi nga ako nakikipag-usap habang nasa loob. Alam ko yung proper behavior sa elevator. The thing is, nasa likod yung bag ko, and baka nasiksik siya because of that. And yes, kasalanan ko rin for not immediately putting it in front, but what made my blood boil was how she handled it. She didn’t say a single word. She pushed me hard. Multiple times. As if she was entitled to that space more than anyone else.

Habang bumababa yung elevator, she kept pushing me in a padabog way. That’s when I turned and looked at her, and she finally opened her mouth, saying nasisikipan daw siya and that I should put my bag in front. I had already tried to distance myself nung una pa lang niya akong tinulak. I even said sorry calmly kahit siya na yung rude sa simula pa lang.

Wala akong intention na maniknik ng tao, I wasn’t moving around pls lang. I was also struggling to move my bag sa harap kasi nga masikip na. And just when I was about to remove my bag to give her peace, she crossed the line. Without hesitation, hinila niya yung strap ng bag ko off my shoulder like she had full authority over my own body and belongings. That wasn’t just rude eh. That was violating. I can still remember you saying "kuya, yung bag dapat nilalagay sa harap hindi sa likod.." nung bigla mong ginrab  yung strap ng bag ko.

I was triggered. Hindi ko alam kung nanghahamon siya ng away, but I chose to remain calm. Still, I felt helpless eh na parang wala akong choice and she acted like may full authority siya na basta-basta hubarin yung bag ko from my body. Do you even realize how demeaning that felt? I was left standing there na mukhang helpless at para bang wala akong magawa but to let her do whatever she wanted.

I decided not to escalate things further. Wala na rin akong energy makipag-away. I’ve started feeling sick lately, and my body’s been tired kasi I also teach students every Sunday. That’s why I just endured it quietly, but deep inside, gusto ko na siyang awayin sa ganung asal niya at that moment.

Paglabas namin, I looked at her face. Naka-grey hoodie, may hikaw, medyo kulot, pero di ko nakita yung ID kung taga-Main or Tech siya para ma identify and meport sa Discipline Unit. Alam kong nakikita niya kami while walking, pero she didn’t even care to look at me na para bang unbothered and even proud pa sa ginawa niya.

Hanggang sa discussion ng next subject, di ako makafocus kasi naiisip ko pa rin yung pagtulak niya at yung biglang paghila ng bag ko. The way she acted na feeling entitled and arrogant? Sobrang nakakabastos at nakakatrigger. 

Ate, you could’ve behaved better if you had even just a little human decency. I never intended na masikipan ka, and sorry kung di ko nailagay agad yung bag ko sa harap. You could’ve simply said “Excuse me, nasisikipan ako.” But no, you chose aggression sa una pa lang.

I even talked about this with my friends, and they noticed na yung kasama mo, inirapan pa yung isa kong kaibigan nung nakasakay kami. We don’t know if you guys were having a bad day, pero monday na monday and umagang-umaga pa lang, may ganung behavior na. Mahirap intindihin yung ganung ugali niyo, to be honest. 

For my fellow students reading this, I’m posting this for awareness and to ask for help: possible po ba na ma-request yung CCTV footage from that elevator so I can have evidence and formally report this to the Discipline Department? I don’t want this to happen again to other students who might ride the elevator with them, especially her. 

No one deserves to be pushed around and treated like someone owns the place!

Pero pagka-close ng door, out of nowhere, bigla akong tinulak. Not just lightly eh, yung tulak na padabog, agresibo, na para bang wala kang respeto. I froze for a second kasi nagulat ako sa ganung behavior. I tried to move a little kasi baka sobrang nasisikipan na siya. Hindi naman kami naglalaro or naghaharutan ng friends ko. Ni hindi nga ako nakikipag-usap habang nasa loob. Alam ko yung proper behavior sa elevator. The thing is, nasa likod yung bag ko, and baka nasiksik siya because of that. And yes, kasalanan ko rin for not immediately putting it in front, but what made my blood boil was how she handled it. She didn’t say a single word. She pushed me hard. Multiple times. As if she was entitled to that space more than anyone else.

For two decades, MarkProf has been shaping future leaders—training over 500 top students who now lead in market innovation and nation-building across major organizations. Each year, hundreds of applicants nationwide aspire to join the prestigious free 8-weekend Marketing and Sales Bootcamp—but only 25 young marketing leaders make it through the rigorous selection process.

Don’t miss this chance to learn more about the MarkProf journey and get tips on how to ace the application process from MarkProf alumni themselves.

𝑷𝒖𝒃𝒍𝒊𝒄𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝑴𝒂𝒕𝒆𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒍 𝒃𝒚: 𝑴𝒊𝒈𝒖𝒆𝒍 𝑫𝒊𝒔𝒊𝒐𝒏

The infamous corruption scandal involving the Department of Public Works and Highways (DPWH), the Discaya couple, and several politicians and contractors came rushing like a flash flood throughout media outlets and social media platforms recently. This became more alarming with the most recent news of the owners of numerous construction firms, Pacifico and Sarah Discaya naming a wide range of local government officials involved in the alleged anomalies in flood control projects. 

It is evident as to how the allocations for infrastructures meant to secure the general public from disasters like floods, typhoons, and heavy rains are anomalously spent: the questionable lavish lifestyle and luxurious possessions (e.g. cars, luxury items, private properties) shamelessly showed off by the Discayas, congress, and representatives (Ombay, 2025), DPWH and government officials (Servallos & Galvez, 2025), and their progeny, commonly coined as “nepo-babies” that are bashed and lifestyle-checked across social media platforms—also considered by the media as a form of activism (De Leon, 2025). 

On September 8, during a televised Senate Blue Ribbon Committee hearing, 17 House of Representatives members and a number of officials from the DPWH demanded 25% kickbacks of project costs, conditionally for the award of flood control contracts (Gomez, 2025). “Mock bidding” was also one of the issues raised, along with “ghost projects,” and inflated or advanced kickbacks. The ghost projects, in particular, were used to describe those that are either non-existent or marked as “accomplished” with no actual progress (Senate of the Philippines’ Press Release, 2025). Particular contractors among the firms owned by the Discayas are Wawao Builders and St. Timothy Construction, which are connected to the anomalies. Along with this, the Commission on Audit (COA) found that the overall worth of flood control projects that are considered as substandard, overpriced, or non-existent were about P341 million (Panti, 2025).

The absurd amount of construction companies, owned by Pacifico II and Sarah Discaya, are alleged to have participated in orchestrated biddings and kickback schemes (Senate of the Philippines’ Press Release, 2025). In an interview, the couple sighs the phrase, “kaya this!” while implicating the involvement of lawmakers like House Speaker Martin Romualdez, Representative Zaldy Co, and many others (Gomez, 2025). Other than lawmakers, several DPWH officials are also under investigation for allegedly supervising project releases, accepting and extorting bribes, and permitting projects with defective features (Servallos and Galvez, 2025). Ultimately, these investigations were led by the COA, the Senate of the Philippines, alongside President Ferdinand Marcos Jr. as he described the situation as “horrible” and called for an independent commission initiative to probe the anomalies (Gomez, 2025). 

With issues on accountability, the public called out for budget scrutiny, particularly highlighting the significant cuts in flood control allocations (Ager, 2025). Former Senate President Francis “Chiz” Escudero suggested deduction of P250.8 billion from the proposed 2026 DPWH flood control allocation, considering the current budget as asymmetrical (Senate of the Philippines’ Press Release, 2025). To elaborate, the widespread public mistrust in the projects’ quality gives rise to the need for reports of substandard materials, the ghost projects, and poor facilitation, which raises questions about whether allocations are accomplishing their intended purpose (Panti, 2025). The public not only calls for accountability and budget deduction, but also for transparency: transactions made by the DPWH to lawmakers without technical vetting or coordination with local government units (Bernardo, 2025). Consequently, it has been estimated that economic losses amount to P118.5 billion in the span of 2023-2025 due to the flood control project anomalies (Inosante, 2025). 

Aside from this, the public came up with more specific questions: First and foremost, the public questioned how are the contractors able to pay or promise heavy kickbacks of 25-40% (Ramos, 2025) and still turn a profit or deliver acceptable work? What is the total amount of flood control budget taken by projects completed in name only, with serious defects, or non-existent? The Filipinos contested on why lawmakers inserted many flood control projects (Bernardo, 2025) without proper feasibility studies, engineering assessments, or LGU coordination. Lastly, they challenged the government on how they will assure the accountability and responsibility of contractors upon the projects’ failures, instead of it falling on the taxpayers money (Senate of the Philippines’ Press Release, 2025) to fund the repairs or reworks due to substandard quality. 

In spite of the public raising such critical questions, lawmakers involved in the Discaya testimony still denied the allegations, like House Speaker Romualdez, who was in denial of receiving benefits from such schemes (Flores, 2025). Nevertheless, the COA and the Office of the Ombudsman are the leading figures in the investigation of the anomalies, with the recent findings of COA about the projects’ defects (Panti, 2025). Even more, some segments from the Congress, particularly of Escudero, suggest the deducted P250.8 billion flood control funds be reallocated in other essential sectors like education, health, and in the food industry. “Mas praktikal at makabubuti na tapyasan na muna ang pondong ilalaan para flood control at ibuhos ito sa mga sektor ng edukasyon, kalusugan, at produksyon ng pagkain habang hinihintay natin ang ADB-funded flood control master plan,”(Senate of the Philippines’ Press Release, 2025). 

Henceforth, the flood control funds controversy posits a critical call for transparency on the spending of taxpayers’ money. Despite its evident corruption and shameless spendings on lavish lifestyles, the situation is still surrounded with ambiguity: 𝙬𝙞𝙡𝙡 𝙩𝙝𝙚 𝙞𝙣𝙨𝙩𝙞𝙩𝙪𝙩𝙞𝙤𝙣𝙨’ 𝙧𝙚𝙨𝙥𝙤𝙣𝙨𝙚 𝙩𝙤 𝙩𝙝𝙞𝙨 𝙞𝙨𝙨𝙪𝙚 𝙧𝙚𝙨𝙪𝙡𝙩 𝙞𝙣 𝙩𝙧𝙪𝙚 𝙧𝙚𝙛𝙤𝙧𝙢𝙖𝙩𝙞𝙤𝙣, 𝙤𝙧 𝙬𝙞𝙡𝙡 𝙡𝙤𝙤𝙥𝙝𝙤𝙡𝙚𝙨 𝙖𝙣𝙙 𝙞𝙢𝙥𝙪𝙣𝙞𝙩𝙮 𝙥𝙧𝙚𝙫𝙖𝙞𝙡? Moving forward, many Filipinos depend on the handling of this controversy with the credibility of future infrastructure projects, their safety, and their overall trust in the government.

𝐓𝐡𝐢𝐬 𝐖𝐨𝐫𝐥𝐝 𝐓𝐨𝐮𝐫𝐢𝐬𝐦 𝐃𝐚𝐲, 𝐜𝐞𝐥𝐞𝐛𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐞 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐭𝐡𝐞𝐦𝐞: “𝐓𝐨𝐮𝐫𝐢𝐬𝐦 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐒𝐮𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐢𝐧𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞 𝐓𝐫𝐚𝐧𝐬𝐟𝐨𝐫𝐦𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧” by embracing responsible travel that benefits local communities, preserves culture, and protects the environment. Voluntourism is a rising trend, especially among Millennials and Gen Z, where travel becomes a meaningful mission to give back through education, conservation, and community projects.

This year, the call for “Tourism and Sustainable Transformation” encourages everyone to rethink how tourism is developed and experienced. It’s about balancing economic growth with preserving natural ecosystems and cultural heritage, while empowering local communities through inclusive policies and innovative practices. 

Together, these efforts transform tourism into a sustainable force that benefits both travelers and the places they visit. 🌍
